## Statistical model — Keyboard reaction time

Secondary outcome model following the preregistered analysis plan.
Keyboard RT is modelled on the log scale using a Gaussian (log-normal) likelihood,
as RT distributions are typically positively skewed.


```{r}
#| eval: false

D_RT <- D_1 |>
  filter(!is.na(keyboard_rt_ms), correct == 1) |>  # valid correct trials only
  mutate(
    log_rt = log(keyboard_rt_ms),
    pre_change_ms_z = scale(pre_change_ms)[,1]
  )

F_RT <- bf(
  log_rt ~ 1 + eccentricity + condition + pre_change_ms_z +
            (1 + eccentricity | Part)
)

Priors_RT <- c(
  set_prior("normal(6, 1)", class = "Intercept"),  # log(400ms) ≈ 6
  set_prior("normal(0, 0.5)", class = "b")
)

M_2 <- brm(
  F_RT,
  data   = D_RT,
  family = gaussian(),
  prior  = Priors_RT,
  chains = 4,
  cores  = 4,
  iter   = 3000,
  warmup = 2000
)

save(M_2, D_RT, file = "M_2_pilot.Rda")
```


```{r}
library(bayr)
load("M_2_pilot.Rda")
P_2 <- bayr::posterior(M_2)
fixef(P_2)
```

Coefficients are on the log scale. To interpret:
- Positive coefficient → longer RT
- Negative coefficient → shorter RT  
- To convert to percentage change: (exp(coefficient) - 1) × 100%

